18 incentives. Sections 9 and 19 of this bill provide for the confidentiality of certain
19 information in the application and for the adoption of regulations. Section 9
20 authorizes the Division to approve such an application if the Division finds that the
21 project meets the qualifications.
22 If the Division approves an application for transferable tax credits, section 10
23 requires the Division to issue to the project sponsor in the qualified project a
24 certificate of eligibility for transferable tax credits. Section 10 provides that a
25 project is eligible for transferable tax credits in an amount equivalent to the costs of
26 financial assistance provided by the project sponsor to purchasers of single-family
27 residences. Section 10 also provides that the expiration of the transferable tax
28 credits is 4 years after the date of issuance to the project sponsor.
29 If the Division approves an application for an abatement, section 11 provides
30 that the project sponsor is entitled to an abatement of: (1) employer excise taxes for
31 a period of not more than 10 years in an amount equal to the amount of the
32 employer excise taxes that would otherwise be owed for the project; and (2) certain
33 local sales and use taxes for a period of not more than 20 years and in an amount
34 equal to those local sales and use taxes that would otherwise be owed in the county
35 in which the project is located. Sections 15 and 16 of this bill make conforming
36 changes as a result of the authorization of these abatements.
37 Section 12 requires the project sponsor to repay any portion of transferable tax
38 credits and any portion of an abatement to which the project sponsor is not entitled
39 if the Division determines that the project sponsor becomes ineligible for the
40 incentives. Section 13 requires the Division to prepare and submit to the
41 Legislature certain reports concerning any tax incentives provided to a project
42 pursuant to sections 2-13.
43 Existing law provides for the assessment of ad valorem taxes on certain real
44 and personal property and provides certain exemptions from those taxes. (Chapter
45 361 of NRS) Section 14 of this bill provides an exemption from the tax on real
46 property for the initial owner of a single-family residence constructed as part of a
47 project approved pursuant to sections 2-13. The Nevada Constitution requires the
48 Legislature to provide a specific date on which an exemption from property taxes
49 will cease to be effective. (Nev. Const. Art. 10, § 6) To comply with this
50 requirement, section 14 prohibits an application for an exemption pursuant to that
51 section from being submitted on or after July 1, 2055. However, an exemption
52 granted pursuant to an application submitted before July 1, 2055, would continue to
53 be in effect until the owner of the residence no longer qualifies for the exemption.
54 Existing law provides for the imposition of taxes on transfers of real property
55 and exempts certain transfers from such taxes. (NRS 375.020, 375.023, 375.026,
56 375.090) Section 17 of this bill exempts the initial transfers of single-family
57 residences constructed in a project approved pursuant to sections 2-13 from the real
58 property transfer tax.
59 Section 18 of this bill prohibits the initial purchaser of a single-family
60 residence in a project approved pursuant to sections 2-13 from selling the single-
61 family residence to a corporation, limited-liability company or affiliate of such an
62 entity.
63 The Nevada Constitution prohibits the Legislature from enacting an exemption
64 from property taxes and sales and use taxes unless the Legislature makes certain
65 findings regarding the benefits and effects of the exemption. (Nev. Const. Art. 10, §
66 6) Section 20 of this bill sets forth such findings of the Legislature with respect to
67 any such exemption provided in this bill.
